dataIdInfo.idAbs: The NOAA MPA Inventory (v2020) is a comprehensive catalog that provides detailed information for existing marine protected areas in the United States. The inventory provides geospatial boundary information (in polygon format) and classification attributes that seek to define the conservation objectives, protection level, governance and related management criteria for all sites in the database. The comprehensive inventory of federal, state and territorial MPA sites provides governments and stakeholders with access to information to make better decisions about the current and future use of place-based conservation. NOTE that this data layer represents IUCN MPAs only. IUCN MPAs are those sites that meet the IUCN definition of protected area as published in 2019 guidelines: 'A protected area is a clearly defined geographical space, recognised, dedicated and managed, through legal or other effective means, to achieve the longterm conservation of nature with associated ecosystem services and cultural values'.
dataIdInfo.idPurp: The NOAA MPA Inventory represents a collection of data compiled from various federal, state, tribal and territorial entities to provide a publicly available source of comprehensive information on place-based marine conservation efforts under U.S. federal, state, territorial, local, and tribal jurisdiction.

dataIdInfo.suppInfo: This dataset consists of original boundaries as represented by the managing agencies, including any terrestrial components of the protected areas. Boundaries include terrestrial areas, but only the sub-tidal components of the areas meet the definition of an MPA. All area-based calculations made using World Eckert IV projection and may vary from areas cited for sites by their managing agency. Version Notes: 2020: Removed all non-IUCN protected areas from 2017 version. Updated IUCN classification for all sites, added new National Marine Sanctuary, added/revised National Wildlife Refuge boundaries and classification, added no-take zones as separate boundaries for some Zoned with No-Take area sites, added/updated NMFS sites in Greater Atlantic and Alaska, reviewed boundaries and classification for National Parks, National Estuarine Research Reserves and Monuments, added new Category field to tag water quality sites, fishery management areas and potential Other Effective Conservation Measure areas. Added URL for sites when available.

dataLineage.statement: All non-IUCN protected areas were removed from previous version. Classification attributes were modified based on input from managing agencies, and review of area regulations.

attr.attrdef: Level of legal protection afforded to the site's natural and cultural resources and ecological processes

edom.edomvd: MPAs or zones with a consistent level of protection and allowable activities, including certain extractive uses, across the entire protected area

MPAs that allow some extractive activities throughout the entire site, but that use marine zoning to allocate specific uses to compatible places or times in order to reduce user conflicts and adverse impacts

MPAs or zones that allow human access, but that prohibit all activities that could harm the site's resources or disrupt the ecological or cultural services they provide. Examples of activities typically prohibited in no-impact MPAs include resource extraction of any kind (fishing, collecting, or mining); discharge of pollutants; disposal or
MPAs or zones that allow human access and even some potentially harmful uses, but that totally prohibit the extraction or significant destruction of natural or cultural resources.

MPAs or zones that restrict all human access to the area in order to prevent potential ecological disturbance, unless specifically permitted for designated special uses such as research, monitoring or restoration
MPA or zone that has been established, but has not yet officially designated it's specific level of protection.
Multiple-use MPAs that contain at least one legally established management zone in which all resource extraction is prohibited
